'''''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix''''' is a [[Cinema of the United Kingdom|British-made]] [[2007 in film|2007]] [[fantasy film|fantasy]] [[adventure film|adventure]] [[film]], based on the [[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix|novel of the same name]], by [[J. K. Rowling]]. Directed by [[David Yates]], it is the fifth film in the popular [[Harry Potter (films)|''Harry Potter'' film series]]. The story follows [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]] entering his fifth year at the [[magic (Harry Potter)|magic]] school [[Hogwarts]]. The [[Ministry of Magic]] is denying the return of [[Lord Voldemort]] and appoints a new teacher, [[Dolores Umbridge]], a [[bureaucrat]] who slowly becomes an authoritarian figure in the school. It is a production of [[David Heyman]]'s company [[Heyday Films]].

The screenplay was written by [[Michael Goldenberg]], who replaced [[Steve Kloves]], writer of the first four films. Live action filming started in February 2006 and finished in the end of November, and post-production on the film continued for several months afterwards. [[Warner Bros.]], the distributor of the film, scheduled a UK release date of [[12 July]] [[2007]], and a U.S. release date of [[11 July]] [[2007]], both in conventional and [[IMAX]] theatres.

The [[List of highest-grossing films|sixth-highest grossing film of all time]], it was a critical and commercial success, and was acclaimed by the author, Rowling, who, unlike some authors, has consistently offered her praise for the film adaptations of her works,<ref name=jk-on-ps-film>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeforkids.com/TFK/specials/potter/0,12405,184807,00.html|title=Potter Power!|work=[[Time For Kids]]|accessdate=2007-05-31}}</ref><ref name=jk-on-poa-film>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2004-05-27-potter-movie-book_x.htm|title=New 'Potter' movie sneaks in spoilers for upcoming books|date=[[2004-05-27]]|accessdate=2007-05-31|work=[[USA Today]]|last=Puig|first=Claudia}}</ref><ref name=jk-on-gof-film>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_4410000/newsid_4415400/4415454.stm|title=JK 'loves' Goblet Of Fire movie|date=[[2005-11-07]]|accessdate=2007-05-31|work=[[BBC]] [[Newsround]]}}</ref> and called ''Order of the Phoenix'' as "the best one yet."<ref name=us-premiere-video-mn>{{cite video|url=http://media.mugglenet.com/movie5/redcarpetvideo/ootpredcarpet.mov|title=OOTP US Premiere red carpet interviews|publisher=[[MuggleNet]]|date=July 8|year=2007|accessdate=2007-07-11|people=[[Rupert Grint|Grint, Rupert]], [[David Heyman]], [[MuggleNet|Emerson Spartz]]}}</ref> 

==Story==
{{seealso|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix}}

The film begins with [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]] and his cousin Dudley mysteriously attacked by two [[Dementors]]. Harry casts the Patronus charm to repel the Dementors, but soon after the Ministry of Magic detect his underage wizardry and inform him that he has been expelled from [[Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry|Hogwarts]]. After experiencing horrible nightmares depicting [[Lord Voldemort]]'s return, Harry is awoken by the arrival of an advance guard of wizards, including [[Mad-Eye Moody]], who escorts him to headquarters of the [[Order of the Phoenix (organisation)|Order of the Phoenix]], a secret organization founded by [[Albus Dumbledore|Dumbledore]]. Members of the Order, including Harry's Godfather [[Sirius Black]], reveal that under the Ministry's influence, the [[Harry Potter newspapers and magazines#The Daily Prophet|The Daily Prophet]] has launched a smear campaign against anyone who claims the Dark Lord has returned, leaving Harry feeling isolated and betrayed by the wizarding community.

With the help of Dumbledore and Harry's neighbor, Mrs. Figg, Harry's name is cleared of all charges at the Ministry and is allowed to return to Hogwarts.  Upon entering his fifth year of school, Harry learns that the Minister for Magic [[Cornelius Fudge]] has appointed a new [[Hogwarts subjects#Defence Against the Dark Arts|Defence Against the Dark Arts]] teacher, [[Dolores Umbridge]], a Senior Ministry official who refuses to teach practical magic to her students, out of fear that Dumbledore will organise his own personal wizard army. As Umbridge's control over the school increases, [[Ron Weasley|Ron]] and [[Hermione Granger|Hermione]] aid Harry in forming a secret defence group, calling themselves "Dumbledore's Army" or DA for short.

During the year, Harry envisions mysterious scenes in his sleep, including a dangerous attack upon [[Arthur Weasley]] in the [[Ministry of Magic#Department of Mysteries|Department of Mysteries]]. Fearing there may be a connection between Voldemort and Harry's mind, [[Severus Snape|Professor Snape]] immediately initiates [[Legilimency#Occlumency|Occlumency]] lessons to close his mind from the Dark Lord's influence.

Promoted to High Inquisitor, Umbridge, [[Argus Filch|Filch]] and her loyal Inquisitorial Squad, including [[Draco Malfoy]], uncover Dumbledore's Army after interrogating one of the students, [[Cho Chang]] for whom Harry had developed intense feelings. Dumbledore is questioned and makes an impressive escape as Fudge orders his arrest. With Dumbledore gone, Umbridge becomes the new Headmistress, and her sinister dominance over the school continues.

During an O.W.L. exam, [[Fred and George Weasley|Fred and George]] launch a firework display causing chaos for Umbridge. As the students cheer joyously outside, Harry suffers a vision of Sirius trapped within the bowels of the Ministry. Umbridge, soon after, catches the trio attempting to use the Floo Network, and begins interrogating Harry. Hermione leads Umbridge into the Forbidden Forest in search of a faux weapon when a herd of [[centaurs]] emerge and carry the Headmistress into the darkness. Finding Ron and other DA members, [[Luna Lovegood]], [[Neville Longbottom]], and [[Ginny Weasley]], they fly to London by winged-horses named [[Thestrals]].  

Arriving at the Ministry, the six enter the Department of Mysteries where they uncover a prophecy named after Harry. Transfixed, they soon become ambushed by Death Eaters, including [[Lucius Malfoy]] and [[Bellatrix Lestrange]], Sirius's deranged cousin. A battle erupts as the Death Eaters try to stop the students from escaping, resulting in Sirius's death at Bellatrix' hand. Back in the Atrium, Harry corners Bellatrix, where she struggles with his desire to enact the Cruciatus curse. Voldemort himself appears, ready to kill Harry when Dumbledore emerges. 

A brief but furious duel takes place, in which Bellatrix escapes through the Floo Network. When Voldemort disappears, and the battle seems over, Harry suddenly finds himself being possessed -- recalling images of his past, of his family and his friends. Seeing Ron and Hermione across the hall,  Harry resists and rebuffs Voldemort, calling the Dark Lord weak. Before Voldemort can kill Harry, Ministry officials, including Fudge, arrive via the Floo Network, seeing the Dark Lord with their own eyes. Voldemort promptly disappears.

In the aftermath, the Ministry is forced to end their smear campaign and Umbridge is removed from Hogwarts, awaiting a formal investigation. Dumbledore explains that he had attempted to distance himself from Harry all year, hoping it would bring less risk as Voldemort would not try to invade his mind. The film ends as Harry tells his friends that they have one thing Voldemort doesn't; something worth fighting for: Love

==Production==
[[David Yates]] was chosen to direct the film after ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]'' director [[Mike Newell (director)|Mike Newell]], as well as [[Jean-Pierre Jeunet]], [[Matthew Vaughn]] and [[Mira Nair]], turned down offers.<ref name=firstew>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20046055,00.html|title=Harry the 5th|accessdate=2007-10-08|last=Daly|first=Steve|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref><ref name=potterbar/> Yates believed he was approached because of one of his previous projects, the television drama ''[[Sex Traffic]]'', and because the studio saw him fit to handle an "edgy and emotional" film with a "political backstory".<ref name=potterbar>{{cite news|url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/review/story/0,,2109781,00.html|title=How I raised Potter's bar|date=[[2007-06-24]]|accessdate=2007-06-26|publisher=[[The Observer]]}}</ref> [[Steve Kloves]], the screenwriter of the first four ''Potter'' films, had other commitments, and [[Michael Goldenberg]] wrote the script for the film.

Rehearsals for ''Order of the Phoenix'' began on [[27 January]] [[2006]], filming began on [[6 February]], and finished in the end of November 2006.<ref name=rehearsals-begin>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/index.php?articleID=8296|title=Order of the Phoenix Movie Rehearsals Starting|date=[[2006-01-27]]|accessdate=2006-12-30|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron}}</ref><ref name=tlc-film-2006-review>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2006/12/29/2006-the-year-in-em-harry-potter-em-film|title=2006: The Year in Harry Potter Film|date=[[2006-12-29]]|accessdate=2006-12-30|publisher=[[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]]}}</ref><ref name=us-premiere-video-mn/> Filming was put on a two-month hiatus starting in May 2006 so that Radcliffe could sit his A/S Levels and Watson could sit her [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] exams.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=18268|title=Exclusive: Order of the Phoenix News|date=[[2006-03-14]]|publisher=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=2007-08-02}}</ref> The film's budget was reportedly between [[Pound sterling|GB<U+00A3>]]75 and 100 million ([[United States dollar|US$]]150 and 200 million).<ref name=scotsman-budget>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/entertainment.cfm?id=121462007|title=Oscars signal boom (except for Scots)|publisher=[[The Scotsman]]|date=[[2007-01-24]]|accessdate=2007-01-24|last=Cornwell|first=Tim}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/features/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003600960&imw=Y|title=Harry the Fifth|first=Harry|last=Haun|publisher=Film Journal International|date=[[2007-06-20]]|accessdate=2007-06-26}}</ref>

[[Mark Day (editor)|Mark Day]] was the film editor, [[S<U+0142>awomir Idziak]] was the cinematographer, and Jany Temime was the costume designer.<ref name=august-press-release>{{cite press release
| url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=176487
| title=Helena Bonham Carter Joins the All-Star Cast and Nicholas Hooper Signs on to Compose the Score of Warner Bros. Pictures' Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix
| date=[[2006-08-02]]
| publisher=[[Warner Bros.]]
| accessdate=2006-10-23
}}</ref> Choreographer [[Paul Harris (choreographer)|Paul Harris]], who has previously worked with David Yates several times, created a physical language for wand combat to choreograph the wand fighting scenes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paulharris.uk.com/Updated/biography.html|title=About Paul Harris|publisher=PaulHarris.uk.com|accessdate=2007-05-30}}</ref>

===Set design===
[[Stuart Craig]] returned as set designer, having also designed the first four films' sets.<ref name=tlc-msnbc-set-photos>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/#article:9484|title=New Interactive OotP Set Preview Photos on MSNBC|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|date=[[2007-02-09]]|accessdate=2007-02-11}}</ref> There were a number of notable new sets in this film. The [[Atrium (architecture)|atrium]] in the [[Ministry of Magic]] is over 200 feet in length, making it the largest and most expensive set yet built for the ''Potter'' film series.<ref name=tlc-msnbc-set-photos/> Craig's design was inspired by early [[London Underground]] stations, where, he said, architects "tried to imitate classical architecture but they used ceramic tile", as well as a [[Burger King]] on [[Tottenham Court Road]] in London, where "there's a fantastic Victorian fa<U+00E7>ade which just embodies the age".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/features/leader/display.var.1443344.0.pottering_about.php|title=Pottering about|date=[[2007-06-02]]|accessdate=2007-06-26|publisher=[[The Northern Echo]]}}</ref><ref name=coming-soon-craig>{{cite news|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/interviewsnews.php?id=21229|title=Harry Potter 5 Set Visit - Production Designer Stuart Craig|last=Newgen|first=Heather|date=[[2007-06-25]]|accessdate=2007-06-26|publisher=ComingSoon.net}}</ref> The set of [[Number Twelve, Grimmauld Place]] contains the [[Black family tree|Black family tapestry]] spread across three walls; when the producers told Rowling they wanted to visualise the details of each name and birth year, she faxed them a complete copy of the entire tree.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2007/5/24/empire-magazine-feature-on-ootp|title="Empire" Magazine Feature on OotP|date=[[2007-05-24]]|accessdate=2007-06-26|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron}}</ref> The set of the Hall of Prophecies was entirely digitally built. During a fight scene which occurs there, prophecies crash to the ground and break; had it been an actual physical set, the reset time would have been weeks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/interviewsnews.php?id=21230|title=Harry Potter 5 Set Visit - The Sets|last=Newgen|first=Heather|date=[[2007-06-25]]|accessdate=2007-06-26|publisher=ComingSoon.net}}</ref>

The set used for [[Igor Karkaroff]]'s trial scene in ''Goblet of Fire'' was doubled in size for Harry's trial in this film, while still protecting its symmetry.<ref name=coming-soon-craig/> New professor Dolores Umbridge, though she teaches in a classroom that has appeared in films two through four, inhabits an office vastly different from those of her predecessors. The set was redressed with "fluffy, pink filigree" and a number of plates upon which moving kittens were animated in post-production.<ref name=vfk-craig>{{cite news|url=http://www.voicesfromkrypton.com/2007/09/an-interview-wi.html#more|title=An Interview with Harry Potter Production Designer Stuart Craig, Part 3|publisher=Voices from Krypton|date=[[2006-09-27]]|accessdate=2007-09-28}}</ref> A 24-hour photo shoot was held to photograph and film the kittens for use on these plates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pottercast.the-leaky-cauldron.org/transcript/show/110?ordernum=1|title=LeakyMug: Order of the Phoenix Set Visit Transcript|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron and MuggleNet|accessdate=2007-09-28}}</ref> Even the elegant quill which Umbridge gives Harry to write lines using his own blood is designed by the set designers.<ref name=vfk-craig/>

For his work on the film, Craig was nominated for an [[Art Directors Guild]] award and [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] award.<ref name=adg-craig>{{cite news|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/awards/guild/env-art-directors-guildnoms11jan11,0,3811812.story?coll=env-guild|title=Art Directors Guild lists nominations and honors for Harryhausen, Craig|date=[[2008-01-11]]|accessdate=2008-01-21|last=King|first=Susan|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref><ref name=bafta-noms>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/film-awards-nominees-in-2008,224,BA.html|title=FILM AWARDS NOMINEES IN 2008|date=[[2008-01-16]]|accessdate=2008-01-21|publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]]}}</ref>

===Filming===
Though the producers explored options to film outside of the UK, [[Leavesden Film Studios|Leavesden Studios]] in [[Watford]] was again the location on which many of the interior scenes, including the [[Hogwarts layout#Great Hall|Great Hall]], [[Little Whinging|Privet Drive]] and [[Number Twelve, Grimmauld Place]] were shot.<ref name=jk-on-gof-film/><ref name=sunrise-watford>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/videogallery/video/show/295|title=Sunrise Behind the Scenes of Order of the Phoenix|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|date=[[2006-03-03]]|accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref><ref name=privet-drive-set-photos>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/index.php?articleID=8815|title=New Privet Drive Set Photos from OotP|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|date=[[2006-07-04]]|accessdate=2007-02-24}}</ref><ref name=leaky-mug-set-preview>{{cite news|url=http://img667.libsyn.com/img667/8224af610faddcbbb7c7ba21e7b15a40/45e065e0/9793/4686/lm14.mp3|title=Leaky Mug: Order of the Phoenix Set Report|publisher=[[The Leaky Mug]]|date=[[2006-11-24]]|accessdate=2007-02-24}}</ref>

Locations in [[England]] included the [[River Thames]], for the flight of the [[Order of the Phoenix (organisation)|Order of the Phoenix]] to Number Twelve, Grimmauld Place, and the flight of Dumbledore's Army to the Ministry of Magic.<ref name=wizard-chase>{{cite news|url=http://www.mugglenet.com/newsfusion/fullnews.php?id=752|publisher=MuggleNet|title=Yates comments on OOTP hold-up|date=[[2005-05-27]]|accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref> This sequence also includes such landmarks as the [[London Eye]], [[Canary Wharf]], [[Clock Tower, Palace of Westminster|Big Ben]], [[Buckingham Palace]], and the [[HMS Belfast]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/hollywood/reviews/harry-potter-order-phoenix-review-200707.html|title=Harry Potter And The Order Of The Phoenix|date=[[2007-07-20]]|accessdate=2007-10-04|publisher=One India|last=Dhanyasree|first=M}}</ref> Filming at Platform 9<U+00BE> took place at [[King's Cross railway station|King's Cross Station]], as it has in the past.<ref name=kings-cross-station-set-report>{{cite news | url=http://hp4unews.blogspot.com/2006/09/kings-cross-sunday-sept-3rd-wonderful.html# | publisher=HP4U News | title=Kings Cross, Sunday Sept 3rd | date=[[2006-09-09]]|accessdate=2006-10-24}}</ref> A telephone booth near [[Scotland Yard]] was used as Harry and Arthur Weasley enter the Ministry,<ref name=hpana-photos-october>{{cite news|url=http://www.hpana.com/news.19639.html|title=New images from 'Order of the Phoenix'|date=[[2006-10-22]]|publisher=HPANA|accessdate=2006-10-22}}</ref> while the crew closed the [[Westminster tube station]] on [[22 October]] [[2006]] to allow for filming of Arthur Weasley accompanying Harry to his trial at the [[Ministry of Magic]].<ref name=westminster-tube>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/6075206.stm|title=Harry Potter rides on London Tube|publisher=BBC|date=[[2006-10-22]]|accessdate=2007-04-01}}</ref> Other scenes were filmed in and around [[Oxford]],<ref name=christ-church-college>{{cite news | url=http://www.harrypotterfanzone.com/fusion/fullnews.php?id=1315 | title=OOTP filming at Oxford's Christ Church College|date = [[2006-09-15]]|publisher=[[Harry Potter Fan Zone]]|accessdate=2006-10-24}}</ref> specifically at nearby [[Blenheim Palace]] in [[Woodstock, Oxfordshire|Woodstock]].<ref name=news-coverage-from-Oxford>{{cite web | url=http://www.oxfordmail.net/news/headlines/display.var.850122.0.harry_potter_pops_into_palace.php | title=Harry Potter pops into palace | publisher=Oxford Mail|date=[[2006-07-27]]|accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref>

Various locations around [[Scotland]] were used for exterior shots. [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]] was used to show 'snow-capped mountains and glens' vital for the opening sequence of the film.<ref name=telegraph-snow>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2006/03/06/nsnow06.xml&sSheet=/news/2006/03/06/ixhome.html|title=Ski Sunday as snow blankets Scotland|date=[[2006-03-06]]|accessdate=2007-04-01|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last=Twinch|first=Emily|coauthors=Henry Samuel}}</ref> In [[Glenfinnan]], the [[Hogwarts Express]] crosses a viaduct, as it has in the past films.<ref name=may-filming-info>{{cite news | url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=14739 | title=Harry Potter 5 Filming in the West Highlands | date = [[2006-05-25]] | publisher = ComingSoon.net|accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref> Aerial scenes were shot in [[Glen Coe]], in Clachaig Gully,<ref name=may-filming-info/> and [[Glen Etive]], which, at the time of filming, was one of the few places in Scotland without snow, making it ideal for a backdrop.<ref name=telegraph-snow/> 

Several locations were used which do not appear in the final cut of the film. In [[Virginia Water]], scenes were shot where Professor McGonagall recovers from Stunning Spells,<ref name=august-set-report>{{cite news | url=http://hp4unews.blogspot.com/2006/08/order-of-phoenix-filming-for-those-of.html|title=Order of the Phoenix Filming|date=[[2006-08-02]]|publisher=HP4U News|accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref> and [[Burnham Beeches]] was used for filming the scene where Hagrid introduces his fifth-year [[Hogwarts subjects#Care of Magical Creatures|Care of Magical Creatures]] class to [[Thestrals]].<ref name=mugglenet-august-set-report>{{cite news | url=http://www.mugglenet.com/app/news/full_story/250|title=Order of the Phoenix August Set Report and Pictures|date=[[2006-08-03]]|publisher=MuggleNet|accessdate=2006-10-24}}</ref> Harry skips stones in front of [[Glenfinnan#Bonnie Prince Charlie|Bonnie Prince Charlie's Monument]] in [[Glenfinnan]] in another cut scene.<ref name=may-filming-info/>

===Visual effects===
Tim Burke was the visual effects supervisor, John Richardson was the special effects supervisor, and Nick Dudman was the creatures special effects supervisor.<ref name=august-press-release/> The film required over 1,400 visual effects shots, and the London-based company [[Double Negative (VFX)|Double Negative]] created more than 950 of them. Working for six months on previsualisation starting in September 2005, Double Negative was largely responsible for sequences in the [[Locations in Hogwarts#Room of Requirement|Room of Requirement]], the [[Locations in Hogwarts#Forbidden Forest|Forbidden Forest]], the [[Hall of Prophecies]], and the [[Ministry of Magic#Department of Mysteries|Death Chamber]].<ref name=vfxworld-pt1>{{cite news|url=http://www.vfxworld.com/?atype=articles&id=3362&page=1|title=Order of the Phoenix: Escalating Potter VFX -- Part 1|date=[[2007-08-01]]|accessdate=2007-08-02|last=Bielik|first=Alain|publisher=VFX World}}</ref>

A new character in the film, [[Grawp]], [[Rubeus Hagrid|Hagrid's]] giant half-brother, came to life by a new technology called Soul Capturing, developed by [http://www.image-metrics.com/ Image Metrics]. Instead of building the character from scratch, the movements and facial expressions of actor [[Tony Maudsley]] were used to model Grawp's actions.<ref name=grawp-cyberface-nyt>{{cite news | last = Waxman | first = Sharon | title = Cyberface: New Technology That Captures the Soul | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = [[2006-10-15]] |accessdate=2007-04-19|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/15/movies/15waxm.html?ex=1318568400&en=15808659d4e4ca69&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss|format=registration required|page=E1}}</ref><ref name=vfxworld-pt1/>

For their work on the film, Burke, Richardson, Emma Norton and Chris Shaw were nominated for a BAFTA award.<ref name=bafta-noms/>

===Score===
{{see also|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (soundtrack)}}
[[Nicholas Hooper]] was the composer for the [[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] of the film, following [[John Williams]], who scored the first three films, and [[Patrick Doyle]], who did the fourth. In the new score, Hooper incorporated variations on "[[Hedwig's Theme]]", the series' theme originally written by Williams for the first film and heard in all subsequent ones.<ref name=fmw-darker-potter>{{cite journal|title=Hooper writes new themes for Potter|last=Carlsson|first=Mikael|date=[[2007-05-08]]|journal=Film Music Weekly|issue=14|pages=4|url=http://www.filmmusicweekly.com/issues/FM_Weekly_050807.pdf|accessdate=2007-05-10}}</ref> In March and April of 2007, Hooper and the [[London Chamber Orchestra]] recorded nearly two hours of music at [[Abbey Road Studios]] in London. The score, like the film and book, is darker than previous instal<!--British spelling-->ments in the series. To emphasise this, the two new main themes reflect the sinister new character [[Dolores Umbridge]], and [[Lord Voldemort]]'s invasion of Harry's mind. A Japanese [[Taiko]] drum was used for a deeper sound in the percussion.<ref name=fmw-darker-potter/> The soundtrack was released on [[10 July]] [[2007]], the eve of the film's release.<ref name=soundtrack-release>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/?articleID=9649|title="Order of the Phoenix" Soundtrack Due July 10|date=[[2007-03-26]]|accessdate=2007-03-26|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron}}</ref>

For his work on the film, Hooper was nominated for a World Soundtrack Discovery Award.<ref name=wsda-hooper>{{cite news|url=http://www.hpana.com/news.20184.html|title=Nicholas Hooper nominated for 'World Soundtrack Discovery Award'|date=2007-09-07|accessdate=2007-09-08|publisher=HPANA}}</ref>

==Cast==
{{further|[[List of Harry Potter films cast members|List of ''Harry Potter'' films cast members]]}}
*'''[[Daniel Radcliffe]]''' as '''[[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]]''', the protagonist. He has to battle with much of the Wizarding world's denial over Harry's encounter with the evil Lord Voldemort at the end of the previous year. He teaches his friends to defend themselves in duels.
*'''[[Rupert Grint]]''' as '''[[Ron Weasley]]''', one of Harry's best friends. He helps Harry found [[Dumbledore's Army]] and accompanies Harry to the [[Ministry of Magic#Department of Mysteries|Department of Mysteries]] in the climax of the film.
*'''[[Emma Watson]]''' as '''[[Hermione Granger]]''', one of Harry's best friends. She helps Harry found Dumbledore's Army and accompanies Harry to the Department of Mysteries in the climax of the film.
*'''[[Ralph Fiennes]]''' as '''[[Lord Voldemort]]''', the antagonist, who lures Harry to the Ministry of Magic and nearly kills him.
*'''[[Michael Gambon]]''' as '''[[Albus Dumbledore]]''', the [[Hogwarts]] headmaster. He upsets Harry by remaining distant from him throughout the year, but explains at the end of the film why he isolated himself. He also explains the meaning of the prophecy to Harry. He also duels with [[Lord Voldemort]] in the climax of the film. 
*'''[[Gary Oldman]]''' as '''[[Sirius Black]]''', Harry's godfather who, during the battle at the Department of Mysteries, is killed by his cousin [[Bellatrix Lestrange]], causing Harry great emotional damage.
*'''[[Imelda Staunton]]''' as '''[[Dolores Umbridge]]''', the new [[Hogwarts subjects#Defence Against the Dark Arts|Defence Against the Dark Arts]] teacher, a plant from the [[Ministry of Magic]] who prevents Harry and his friends from learning practical magic, and refuses to allow Harry to claim that Lord Voldemort has returned.
*'''[[Alan Rickman]]''' as '''[[Severus Snape]]''', the [[Hogwarts subjects#Potions|Potions]] master. He helps teach Harry to block his mind's connection to Lord Voldemort's. He holds a grudge against Harry because he and Harry's father hated each other while they were at school together.
*'''[[Helena Bonham Carter]]''' as '''[[Bellatrix Lestrange]]''', one of Lord Voldemort's right-hand [[Death Eater]]s who leads the battle at the Department of Mysteries. 
*'''[[Jason Isaacs]]''' as '''[[Lucius Malfoy]]''', one of Lord Voldemort's right-hand [[Death Eater]]s who leads the battle at the Department of Mysteries. 
*'''[[Tom Felton]]''' as '''[[Draco Malfoy]]''', Harry's rival. He supports Umbridge and helps her capture Dumbledore's Army.
*'''[[Matthew Lewis (actor)|Matthew Lewis]]''' as '''[[Neville Longbottom]]''', a classmate of Harry's who accompanies him to the Department of Mysteries.
*'''[[Evanna Lynch]]''' as '''[[Luna Lovegood]]''', a schoolmate of Harry's who explains the [[Thestrals]] to him and accompanies him to the Department of Mysteries.
*'''[[Bonnie Wright]]''' as '''[[Ginny Weasley]]''', Ron's sister who accompanies Harry to the Department of Mysteries.
*'''[[Katie Leung]]''' as '''[[Cho Chang]]''', Harry's love interest, who betrays Dumbledore's Army.
*'''[[Robbie Coltrane]]''' as '''[[Rubeus Hagrid]]''', the regular [[Hogwarts subjects#Care of Magical Creatures|Care of Magical Creatures]] professor, and close friend of Harry, Ron and Hermione. He is absent for the first half of the year on a mission for the [[Order of the Phoenix (organisation)|Order of the Phoenix]].
*'''[[Maggie Smith]]''' as '''[[Minerva McGonagall]]''', the [[Hogwarts subjects#Transfiguration|Transfiguration]] teacher and deputy headmistress.
*'''[[Emma Thompson]]''' as '''[[Sybill Trelawney]]''', the [[Hogwarts subjects#Divination|Divination]] teacher who Umbridge fires for not being able to correctly divine the future.
*'''[[David Thewlis]]''' as '''[[Remus Lupin]]''', a former Hogwarts teacher and mentor of Harry. He is a member of the [[Order of the Phoenix (organisation)|Order of the Phoenix]] and participates in the battle at the Department of Mysteries. 
*'''[[Brendan Gleeson]]''' as '''[[Alastor Moody|Alastor "Mad-Eye" Moody]]''', a retired [[Auror]]. He is a member of the Order of the Phoenix and participates in the battle at the Department of Mysteries.  
*'''[[George Harris (actor)|George Harris]]''' as '''[[Kingsley Shacklebolt]]''', an Auror and a member of the Order of the Phoenix who participates in the battle at the Department of Mysteries. 
*'''[[Natalia Tena]]''' as '''[[Nymphadora Tonks]]''', an Auror and member of the Order of the Phoenix who participates in the battle at the Department of Mysteries. 
*'''[[Julie Walters]]''' as '''[[Molly Weasley]]''', Ron's mother who acts as a maternal figure to Harry.
*'''[[Mark Williams (actor)|Mark Williams]]''' as '''[[Arthur Weasley]]''', Ron's father who acts as a paternal figure to Harry. Harry saves him from death when he sees a vision of Arthur being attacked.
*'''[[James and Oliver Phelps]]''' as '''[[Fred and George Weasley]]''', respectively, Ron's twin brothers who leave Hogwarts on broomstick amidst fireworks in defiance of Umbridge.
*'''[[Robert Hardy]]''' as '''[[Cornelius Fudge]]''', the Minister for Magic, who refuses to believe that Lord Voldemort has returned.
*'''[[Harry Melling (actor)|Harry Melling]]''' as '''[[Dursley Family#Dudley Dursley|Dudley Dursley]]''', Harry's cousin who bullies him and is attacked by [[Dementor]]s.
*'''[[Richard Griffiths]]''' as '''[[Dursley Family#Vernon Dursley|Vernon Dursley]]''' and '''[[Fiona Shaw]]''' as '''[[Dursley Family#Petunia Dursley|Petunia Dursley]]''', Harry's uncle and aunt who dote on their son.
*'''[[Timothy Bateson]]''' as the voice of '''[[Kreacher]]''', the disgruntled house-elf of the Black family.

===Casting===
Casting began as early as May 2005, when Radcliffe announced he would reprise his role as Harry.<ref name=USA-today-dan>{{cite news | url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2005-05-03-potter-sidebar_x.htm | work=[[USA Today]] | title=There's no looking back | date=[[2005-05-03]] | accessdate=2006-10-23 | last=Puig | first=Claudia}}</ref> Across the media frenzy that took place during the release of ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Goblet of Fire]]'' ([[2005 in film|2005]]), most of the main returning actors announced their return to the series, including Grint, Watson, Lewis, Wright, Leung, and Fiennes.<ref name=rupert-NR>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_4440000/newsid_4443900/4443956.stm | work=[[BBC]] | title=NR chats to GOF's Rupert Grint | date=[[2005-11-16]] | accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref><ref name=emma-NR>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_4440000/newsid_4443700/4443762.stm | work=BBC | title=NR chats to GOF's Emma Watson  | date=[[2005-11-16]] | accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref><ref name=mn-chat-matt-lewis>{{cite news | url = http://www.mugglenet.com/chat/transcripts/mattlewis250805.htm | title=Matthew Lewis: Online Q&A session | publisher=MuggleNet | date = [[2005-08-25]] | accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref><ref name=wright-scholastic>{{cite news | url=http://teacher.scholastic.com/scholasticnews/indepth/harry_potter_movie_iv/interviews/index.asp?article=wright&topic=1 | title=Bonnie Wright as Ginny Weasley in ''Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'' | work=Scholastic News | date=[[2005-11-26]] | accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref><ref name=leung-the-star>{{cite web | url=http://thestar.com.my/youth2/story.asp?file=/2005/11/16/youth2/12553500&sec=youth2 | title=What Katie did | publisher=The Star (Malaysia) | date=[[2005-11-16]] | accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref><ref name=fiennes-comingsoon>{{cite news | url = http://www.comingsoon.net/news/topnews.php?id=10724 | title=Ralph Fiennes on Lord Voldemort | publisher=ComingSoon.net | date=[[2005-08-09]] | accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref>

A number of characters new to the series appear in the film. Staunton announced she would be playing the major new role of Dolores Umbridge in October 2005,<ref name=staunton-bbc>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_4360000/newsid_4365800/4365880.stm | title=Top actress 'will play Umbridge' | publisher = BBC | date=[[2005-10-21]] | accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref> and the announcements of the casting of the rest of the new characters to the series was spanned across 2006. Lynch won the role of [[Luna Lovegood]] over 15,000 other girls who attended the open casting call,<ref name=coming-soon>{{cite news|url=http://comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=13018|publisher = ComingSoon.net|title = Filming Begins for ''Harry Potter 5''| date=[[2006-02-02]]|accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref> waiting in a line of hopefuls that stretched a mile long.<ref name=lizo-luna-report>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_4610000/newsid_4615000/4615092.stm|title=Lizo reports from the Luna casting|date=[[2006-01-15]]|accessdate=2006-10-24|publisher=BBC}}</ref> On [[1 April]] [[2006]], [[Helen McCrory]], who had been signed on to play Bellatrix Lestrange,<ref name=bbc-lovegood>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_4670000/newsid_4672700/4672798.stm | publisher = BBC | title = Luna Lovegood role has been cast | date = [[2006-02-02]] | accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref> announced that she was three months' pregnant and had to withdraw from the film. On [[25 May]] [[2006]] the [[BBC]] reported that [[Helena Bonham Carter]] would play the role instead.<ref name=new-bellatrix>{{cite news  | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_5010000/newsid_5015300/5015376.stm | title= Potter exclusive: New Bellatrix | date=[[2006-05-25]] | publisher=BBC | accessdate=2006-10-23}}</ref>

The inclusion or cutting of some characters sparked speculation from fans as to the importance of the characters in the [[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows|final book]] of the series. In April 2006, representatives of [[Jim McManus]] said he would be playing [[Aberforth Dumbledore]], Albus' brother and the barman of the Hog's Head, in which Harry and his friends found the D.A. A week later WB announced that the role was "very minor", allaying some of the speculation to the significance of the role, which, before the final book, was not even a speaking part.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2006/4/26/wb-mcmanus-as-aberforth-very-minor-role|title=WB: McManus as Aberforth, "Very Minor Role"|date=[[2006-04-26]]|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|accessdate=2007-08-25}}</ref> [[MTV]] reported in October 2006 that [[Dobby]], a house-elf who appeared in the second film, ''[[Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)|Chamber of Secrets]]'' ([[2002 in film|2002]]), and in the fifth book, would be cut, opening up "plot questions" as to how the role of the elf would be filled.<ref name=dobby-mtv>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/movies/news/articles/1542581/10062006/story.jhtml | title=Elf's Absence From Next 'Harry Potter' Flick Opens Up Plot Questions | publisher=[[MTV]] | date=[[2006-10-06]] | accessdate=2006-10-06|last=Adler|first=Shawn}}</ref> MTV also reported about a month before the release of the final book that [[Kreacher]], the Black family's house-elf, was cut from the film in one draft of the script. However, after Rowling prodded the filmmakers to include him, saying, "You know, I wouldn't [cut him] if I were you. Or you can, but if you get to make a seventh film, you<U+2019>ll be tied in knots", he was added back into the script.<ref name=kreacher-mtv>{{cite news|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2007/06/25/kreacher-comforts-mtv-solves-a-harry-potter-mystery|title=Kreacher Comfort: MTV Solves A <U+2018>Harry Potter<U+2019> Mystery|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=[[2007-06-25]]|accessdate=2007-06-26|last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer}}</ref>

Other minor roles were cut with subsequent drafts of the script. At the U.S. premiere of ''Goblet of Fire'', series producer [[David Heyman]] said that former Hogwarts professor [[Gilderoy Lockhart]], played by [[Kenneth Branagh]] in ''[[Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)|Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets]]'' ([[2002 in film|2002]]), was in the first draft of the script for ''Phoenix''.<ref name=red-carpet-video>{{cite video | url=http://www.mugglenet.com/movieViewer.php?u=http://media.mugglenet.com/20051127-gofredcarpetinterviews/20051127-gofredcarpetinterviews.mov&w=320&h=240&l=Goblet+of+Fire+Red+Carpet+Interviews%2C+Part+2&c=Interviews+filmed+with+Tolga+Safer%2C+David+Heyman%2C+Miranda+Richardson%2C+and+Dan+Radcliffe+on+the+red+carpet+of+the+US+premiere. | title="Goblet of Fire" Red Carpet Interviews, Part 2: Interviews filmed with Tolga Safer, David Heyman, Miranda Richardson, and Dan Radcliffe on the red carpet of the US premiere. | accessdate=2006-06-06 | format=[[QuickTime]] | date=November 13|year=2005 | people=Anelli, Melissa, [[David Heyman]], [[Daniel Radcliffe]], [[Miranda Richardson]], [[Tolga Safer]], Emerson Spartz | publisher=The Leaky Cauldron, MuggleNet}}</ref> However, neither Branagh nor the character of Lockhart appears in the final version. [[Tiana Benjamin]] was scheduled to return for the film in the role of [[Minor characters associated with Quidditch#Angelina Johnson|Angelina Johnson]], the captain of the [[Hogwarts houses#Gryffindor|Gryffindor]] [[Quidditch]] team, but she had to withdraw due to a commitment to playing [[Chelsea Fox]] in ''[[EastEnders]]''. The character, as well as the entire Quidditch subplot, was ultimately cut from the film. She did, however, record sound clips for the [[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (video game)|''Order of the Phoenix'' video game]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/a44522/tiana-benjamin.html?page=4|title=Tiana Benjamin|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=[[2007-04-13]]|accessdate=2007-04-15|last=Green|first=Kris}}</ref>

The family of footballer [[Theo Walcott]] made a cameo role in the film. Theo himself was due to appear as well, though his commitments to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] forced him to pull out.<ref name=walcott-cameo>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2093-2372152,00.html|date=[[2006-09-24]]|title=Football Shorts: Theo misses out on Harry Potter film|publisher=[[The Times]]|accessdate=2006-10-24}}</ref>

==Differences from the book==
At 766 pages in the British edition and 870 in the American edition, ''Order of the Phoenix'' is the longest ''Harry Potter'' book in the series.<ref name=ewdif>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20045813,00.html|title=What ''Phoenix'' leaves out|accessdate=2007-10-09|author=Daly, Steve|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Screenwriter [[Michael Goldenberg]] described his task to cut down the novel as searching for "the best equivalent way to tell the story. My job was to stay true to the spirit of the book, rather than to the letter".<ref name=salon-goldenberg>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/ent/movies/feature/2007/07/11/goldenberg_qa/|title=Harry Potter and the art of screenwriting|date=[[2007-07-11]]|accessdate=2007-09-15|last=Traister|first=Rebecca|publisher=[[Salon.com]]}}</ref> Goldenberg said that Rowling told him, the producers, and Yates that "she just wanted to see a great movie, and gave [them] permission to take whatever liberties [they] felt [they] needed to take to translate the book into a movie she would love".<ref name=salon-goldenberg/> Cutting down the book to meet the time frame of the film, Goldenberg explained, became "clearer when [he] figured out that the organizing principle of the screenplay was to narrate Harry's emotional journey".<ref name=salon-goldenberg/> He and Yates "looked for every opportunity to get everything [they] could in there. And where [they] couldn't, to sort of pay homage to it, to have it somewhere in the background or to feel like it could be taking place off-screen."<ref name=tlc-goldenberg>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2007/4/10/introducing-michael-goldenberg-the-ootp-scribe-on-the-em-harry-potter-em-films-franchise-and-fandom|title=Introducing Michael Goldenberg: The OotP scribe on the Harry Potter films, franchise, and fandom|date=[[2007-04-09]]|accessdate=2007-09-15|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|last=Anelli|first=Melissa}}</ref>

One cut Goldenberg had to make, which he "hated" to do, was the absence of [[Quidditch]], the wizarding sport.<ref name=tlc-goldenberg/> "The truth is that any movie made of this book, whoever made it, that had included the Quidditch subplot would have been a lesser film," he said.<ref name=salon-goldenberg/> In the book, Ron grows as a character by trying out for the Quidditch team. "Ron facing challenges and coming into his own in the same way that Harry is, we tried to get that into the film in other ways, as much as possible. So, you feel like, if not the details of that story, at least the spirit of it is present in the film."<ref name=salon-goldenberg/> The change disappointed Grint who had been "quite looking forward to the Quidditch stuff."<ref name=secondew>{{cite news|title='Phoenix' Rising|date=[[2007-04-06]]|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20016352,00.html|last=Daly|first=Steve|accessdate=2007-04-01}}</ref>

In a significant scene in the book, Harry sees a memory of his own father humiliating Snape in their school days, and Snape insulting his mother after she stood up for him. In the film, it is abbreviated to an "idea", in Goldenberg's words. "It's an iconic moment when you realize your parents are normal, flawed human beings. <U+2026> Things get trimmed out, but I kept the meat of that in there <U+2014> and that was what really gave me the coming-of-age story."<ref name=salon-goldenberg/> Young [[James and Lily Potter|Lily Potter]] did not appear at all, but promotional screenshots show unknown teenager Susie Shinner in the role.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=16664789%26method=full%26siteid=66633%26headline=magic%2dparents%2d-name_page.html|title=Magic Parents|date=[[2007-02-04]]|accessdate=2007-09-15|publisher=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]}}</ref>

The scene at [[St Mungo's (Harry Potter)|St Mungo's]], the hospital where Harry runs into classmate [[Neville Longbottom]] and learns that his parents were tortured into insanity by [[Bellatrix Lestrange]], was cut because it required the construction of a new set.<ref name=salon-goldenberg/> The main purpose of the action of the scene was relocated to the [[Room of Requirement]] after one of the D.A. lessons. Also, in order to speed up the film's climax, several events in the Ministry leading up to Harry's battle with Voldemort were removed, including the brain room.<ref name=ewdif/> Mrs. Weasley's encounter with a boggart at [[Grimmauld Place]], Ron, Hermione and Malfoy becoming prefects, and Firenze teaching Divination followed suit.<ref name=secondew/>

The character of [[Kreacher]] the house-elf, who was included in the script only at Rowling's request, has a larger part in the book than the film. In the novel, he is seen saving some of the Black family's artifacts which the Order of the Phoenix throw away, one of which is a locket which becomes extremely important in the seventh book.<ref>[[J. K. Rowling|Rowling, J.&nbsp;K.]] (2007). ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'' (in English). [[London]]: [[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]]/[[New York City]]: [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]], et al. UK ISBN 1551929767/U.S. ISBN 0545010225, chapter 10.</ref> "It was kind of tricky to raise that in our story, because it's for so much later," Yates said. "We figured we can probably introduce it later, and that's the approach we took".<ref name=kreacher-mtv/> Whilst Kreacher remained, all scenes involving [[Dobby]] were cut, and his important actions given to other characters.<ref name=ewdif/>

[[Rita Skeeter]], the journalist played by [[Miranda Richardson]] in ''Goblet of Fire'', was also removed. In the book, Hermione blackmails her into writing articles that support Harry as the rest of the wizarding world denies his claims.<ref name=ewdif/> Richardson noted that "it's never gonna be the book on film, exactly. <U+2026> They'll take certain aspects from the book and make it something that they hope is going to be commercial and that people want to see."<ref name="gof-red-carpet-video">{{cite web
 | url=http://www.mugglenet.com/movieViewer.php?u=http://media.mugglenet.com/20051127-gofredcarpetinterviews/20051127-gofredcarpetinterviews.mov&w=320&h=240&l=Goblet+of+Fire+Red+Carpet+Interviews%2C+Part+2&c=Interviews+filmed+with+Tolga+Safer%2C+David+Heyman%2C+Miranda+Richardson%2C+and+Dan+Radcliffe+on+the+red+carpet+of+the+US+premiere.
 | title=''Goblet of Fire'' Red Carpet Interviews, Part 2: Interviews filmed with Tolga Safer, David Heyman, Miranda Richardson, and Dan Radcliffe on the red carpet of the US premiere.
 | accessdate=2007-09-15
 | format=[[QuickTime]]
 | publisher=The Leaky Cauldron, MuggleNet
 }}</ref>

In the novel, one of [[Cho Chang]]'s friends betrays [[Dumbledore's Army]], but in the movie Chang herself does it because [[Dolores Umbridge]] makes her drink [[Veritaserum]].  The ''[[Levicorpus]]'' spell is used on two occasions in the [[film]]: it is practiced during one of the meetings of Dumbledore's Army, and Luna Lovegood uses it on a [[Death Eater]] in the Ministry of Magic; but Harry doesn't learn the spell until the sixth [[book]] of the series, ''[[Harry Potter and the Half Blood Prince]]'', when he finds it written in the margin of his potions book.  The spell used in the death of [[Sirius Black]] is also changed in the film.  In the book Sirius is hit by a  red-coloured curse from Bellatrix and falls through The Veil in the Death Chamber. Bellatrix yells "''[[Avada Kedavra]]''" to kill Sirius, ''then'' he falls through the veil in the film. Another addition was that the Death Eaters could apparently fly. This may be the film's portrayal of [[apparation]], although apparation is never mentioned in the film.

The final sequence at the Ministry of Magic is much condensed from the novel, and while most Potter's group are shown receiving scratches and bruises, events such as Hermione nearly being killed by a Death Eater curse, Ginny breaking her knee, and Neville's nose being broken (preventing him from casting spells properly) are omitted.

Once again, the subplot concerning [[Hermione Granger]]'s house-elf rights advocate organization S.P.E.W (Society for the Promotion of Elfish Welfare) is absent from the film. Hermione's displeasure at the slavery of house-elves is considerably dimmed as well. Although this becomes more important in the seventh book, when Ron finally proves himself worthy of Hermione's affections by defending the elves, it is removed from the plot of the movie adaptations.

When discussing Harry's kiss with Cho Chang, and how she was crying about something, Hermoine mentions Cho could be stressed over multiple things. One of which is taking her O.W.L's. However, Since Cho is a year above Harry, Ron, and Hermoine, Cho would have already taken her O.W.L's in the previous year.

==Distribution==
===Marketing===
[[Image:Potter-bus.jpg|thumb|240px|A London bus, adorned with an advertisement for film.]]
The first [[trailer (film)|trailer]] was released on [[November 17]] [[2006]], attached to another WB film, ''[[Happy Feet]]''. It was made available online on [[November 20]] [[2006]], on the ''Happy Feet'' website.<ref name=trailer-info>{{cite news|url=http://leakynews.com/#article:9234|title=Order of the Phoenix Trailer to Show on Happy Feet Website Monday November 20 at 3:00pm (EST)|publisher=[[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]]|date=2006-11-17|accessdate=2006-11-20}}</ref> The international trailer debuted online on [[April 22]] [[2007]] at 14:00 [[UTC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/?articleID=9737|title=New International Trailer for "Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix"|date=[[2007-04-22]]|accessdate=2007-04-22|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron}}</ref> On [[May 4]] [[2007]], the domestic trailer was shown before ''[[Spider-Man 3]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2007-04-22-harry-potter-trailer_N.htm?csp=34|title='Phoenix' is born again in new trailer|publisher=USA Today|last=Puig|first=Claudia|date=[[2007-04-22]]|accessdate=2007-04-23}}</ref> 

Two posters released on the Internet that showed Harry accompanied by six classmates, including [[Hermione Granger]], generated some controversy by the media. They were essentially the same picture, though one advertised the [[IMAX]] release. In one poster, the profile of Hermione, played by [[Emma Watson]], was made curvier as the outline of her breasts was enhanced. Melissa Anelli, webmistress of noted fan site [[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]], wrote:<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/index.php#article:9797|title=Ch-ch-changes on the OotP Posters|last=Anelli|first=Melissa|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|date=[[2007-05-04]]|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref>
{{cquote|Emma Watson is playing a 15-year-old girl, and she herself is under 18. I get the full heebie jeebies thinking about the person who sat there thinking, 'Now, if we cinch her waist a bit, and inflate her bust a bit, and give her some dramatic lighting and more blonde hair, this would be a much better picture.'}}

Representatives for WB later wrote about the poster under fire, "This is not an official poster. Unfortunately this image was accidentally posted on the IMAX website".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/showbiz/showbiznews.html?in_article_id=452961&in_page_id=1773|title=Harry Potter and the mystery of Hermione's curves|last=Tapper|first=James|date=[[2007-05-05]]|accessdate=2007-05-10|publisher=Daily Mail}}</ref>

The [[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (video game)|video game version]], designed by [[EA UK]], was released [[June 25]] [[2007]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2007/6/4/trick-out-your-broom-at-ootp-video-game-preview-events|title="Trick Out Your Broom" at OotP Video Game Preview Events|date=[[2007-06-04]]|accessdate=2007-07-02|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron}}</ref> [[Lego]] produced [[Lego Harry Potter#Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix|just one set]], a model of Hogwarts, the lowest amount of sets for a film so far.<ref name=merc>{{cite news|url=http://mugglenet.com/app/news/show/646|title=New 'Phoenix' merchandise info|accessdate=2007-10-08|date=[[2007-02-13]]|publisher=MuggleNet}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mugglenet.com/app/news/archive/2007/02|title=LEGO not producing any additional OOTP sets|accessdate=2007-10-08|date=[[2007-02-20]]|publisher=MuggleNet}}</ref> [[National Entertainment Collectibles Association|NECA]] produced a series of [[action figures]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.figures.com/databases/action.cgi?setup_file=fignews2.setup&category=actionfigures&topic=155&show_article=388&nl=1|title=TF07: NECA Checks into Hogwarts School of Witchcraft & Wizardry |accessdate=2007-10-08|publisher=Figures.com}}</ref> whilst a larger array of smaller figures was also produced by PopCo Entertainment, a Corgi International company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harrypotterfanzone.com/gallery/thumbnails.php?album=236|title=Forbidden Planet Preview|accessdate=2007-10-08|publisher=[[Harry Potter Fan Zone]]}}</ref>

===Release===
The film was the third ''Harry Potter'' film to be given a simultaneous release in conventional theatres and IMAX. The IMAX release featured the full movie in 2-D and the final 20 minutes of the film in 3-D.<ref name=prnewswire-release>{{cite press release | url=http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&STORY=/www/story/04-19-2007/0004569017&EDATE= | title=Warner Bros. Pictures' Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix to feature IMAX(R) 3D Finale | date=[[2007-04-19]]|accessdate=2007-04-19| publisher=[[IMAX Corporation]]}}</ref> According to estimates in March 2007, by [[Warner Bros.]], the film would debut on over 10,000 theatre screens during the summer.<ref name=10000-theaters>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117960466.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=Big hopes for a summer abroad|last=McNary|first=Dave|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=[[2007-03-03]]|accessdate=2007-03-04}}</ref>

The film was released in most countries in a two-week period starting [[11 July]] [[2007]]. WB has tried to stick with day-and-date releases for most countries "except in the Middle East and a few minor markets, because most are going to be in holidays at that point". The set of summer releases, even though the films are typically released in the winter, "really maximizes our opportunity," said a representative for WB.<ref name=10000-theaters/>

Previews of the film began in March 2007 in the [[Chicago]] area.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mugglenet.com/app/news/show/703|title=First review of 'Order of the Phoenix'|date=[[2007-03-05]]|accessdate=2007-06-21|publisher=MuggleNet}}</ref> Under tight security to prevent piracy, WB had security guards patrol the aisles, looking for cell phone cameras or small recording devices, at a preview in Japan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantoday.com/jp/news/409873|title=Security tight as Japan fans get first look at new 'Harry Potter' movie|date=[[2007-06-20]]|accessdate=2007-06-21|last=Betros|first=Chris|publisher=[[Japan Today]]}}</ref> The world premiere took place in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] on [[28 June]] [[2007]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6679263.stm|title=Japanese debut for Potter movie|date=[[2007-05-22]]|accessdate=2007-05-26|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> [[MySpace]] users could bring copies of their online profiles to gain free admission to sneak previews in eight different cities across the country on [[28 June]] [[2007]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hpana.com/news.20009.html|title=Free, early 'Potter' screenings for MySpace members|date=[[2007-06-25]]|accessdate=2007-07-11|publisher=HPANA}}</ref> The UK premiere took place on [[3 July]] [[2007]] in [[London]]'s [[Odeon Leicester Square]], during which author [[J. K. Rowling]] made a public appearance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6266590.stm|title=Fans brave rain for Potter stars|date=[[2007-07-03]]|accessdate=2007-07-04|publisher=BBC}}</ref> The U.S. premiere took place on [[8 July]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mugglenet.com/app/news/show/894|title='Order of the Phoenix' US premiere confirmed|date=[[2007-05-15]]|accessdate=2007-05-22|publisher=MuggleNet}}</ref> After the premiere, the three young stars of the film series, Radcliffe, Grint, and Watson, were honoured with a ceremony where their handprints, footprints, and "wandprints" were placed in the cement in front of [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://home.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/index.jsp?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20070522006318&newsLang=en|title=HARRY POTTER AND THE ORDER OF THE PHOENIX: Daniel Radcliffe, Rupert Grint and Emma Watson to Be Honored with Hand, Foot and Wand-Print Ceremony at Grauman<U+2019>s Chinese Theatre|date=[[2007-05-22]]|publisher=Warner Bros.|accessdate=2007-05-22}}</ref>

The film was released on the following dates in these major English-speaking countries:<ref name=release-dates-wb-official>{{cite web|url=http://harrypotter.warnerbros.co.uk/countries/countries.html|title=Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix <U+2013> Worldwide Release Dates|accessdate=2007-06-05|publisher=Warner Bros.}}</ref>

*[[Malaysia]], [[Australia]], [[Canada]], [[Hong Kong]],  [[New Zealand]], [[South Africa]], [[Philippines]], [[United States]] &mdash; [[11 July]]
*[[Puerto Rico]], [[Singapore]], [[United Kingdom]] &mdash; [[12 July]] 
*[[Republic of Ireland]], [[India]] &mdash; [[13 July]] 

Originally, Warner Bros. set the [[Australia]]n release date as [[6 September]] [[2007]], nearly two months after the majority of other release dates. However, after complaints from the Australian community, including a petition garnering 2,000 signatures, the date was pulled back to [[11 July]] [[2007]].<ref name=australia-release-dates>{{cite news|url=http://www.harrypotterfanzone.com/fusion/fullnews.php?id=1840|title='Order of the Phoenix' release date changed in Australia|publisher=[[Harry Potter Fan Zone]]|date=[[2007-06-16]]|accessdate=2007-06-16}}</ref> The release dates of the film in the UK and U.S. were also moved back, both from [[13 July]], to [[12 July]] and [[11 July]], respectively.<ref name=uk-date-change>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/index.php?articleID=9831|title=Change to UK "OotP" Date: Now July 12|date=[[2007-05-11]]|accessdate=2007-05-29|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron}}</ref><ref name=us-date-change>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/?articleID=9905|title=Confirmed: Change to US "Order of the Phoenix" Release Date, Now July 11|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|date=[[2007-05-29]]|accessdate=2007-05-29}}</ref>

Even though the book is the longest in the series, the film is 138 minutes long, the shortest in the entire film series.<ref name="bbfc">{{cite web |url= http://www.bbfc.co.uk/website/Classified.nsf/e8ea0df3a881175480256d58003cb570/54810dfdf91b90db802572e6006306a0?OpenDocument|title= Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix rated 12A by the BBFC|accessdate=2007-06-01|date=[[2007-05-24]]|publisher= [[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC.co.uk]]}}</ref> In the [[motion picture rating system]], it was rated the equivalent of the U.S.'s PG-13, the UK's 12A, and Australia's M, although in Canada, the film was only rated PG, and G in [[Quebec]]. Reasons for the ratings were variations on "fantasy violence" and "dark themes".<ref name=australia-rating>{{cite news|url=http://theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,21901928-2702,00.html?from=public_rss|title=Potter's M is not for magic|date=[[2007-06-14]]|accessdate=2007-06-14|publisher=[[The Australian]]|last=Bodey|first=Michael}}</ref>

====DVD====
A 2-disc special edition DVD, as well as a [[fullscreen (cinema)|fullscreen]] and a [[widescreen]] edition of the film was released on [[12 November]] [[2007]] in the U.K., [[14 November]] [[2007]] in [[Australia]], and [[11 December]] [[2007]] in the US and Canada, with the [[HD DVD]] and [[Blu-Ray Disc]] releases of the film occurring on the same date in each respective country.

Extras appearing on the DVDs include additional scenes, a feature trailing a day in the life of [[Natalia Tena]], who played [[Nymphadora Tonks]], an [[A&E]] documentary about the films and books, and a featurette on film editing in ''Phoenix''. The DVD-ROM features a timeline and a sneak peek of the next film, ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' ([[2008 in film|2008]]). The HD DVD and Blu-Ray contain additional features, such as the "in-movie experience", a video commentary in which members of Dumbledore's Army share their favourite moments from the production of the film, and "focus points" featurettes on how certain scenes of the film were made.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.noblepr.co.uk/Press_Releases/warner/harry_potter_phoenix.htm|title=The rebellion begins on 12th November 2007!|date=[[2007-09-17]]|accessdate=2007-09-19|publisher=Warner Bros.}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://home.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/index.jsp?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20070917006585&newsLang=en|title=Flying onto DVD for the Holidays: Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix Available December 11 from Warner Home Video|date=[[2007-09-17]]|accessdate=2007-09-19|publisher=Warner Bros.}}</ref>
Warner has noticed that the Blu-ray release has sold more. Warner decided to support Blu-ray because of the sales.

There was also a third DVD with extras featuring a behind the scenes look at the sets of the movie. This can only be found in those purchased at [[Target Corporation|Target]] stores as it is a Target exclusive. The package included a one-time-only code that activated a digital copy of the film, which may be played on a computer with Windows Media Player. The digital copy however is not playable on [[Macintosh]] or [[Apple Inc.]] [[iPod]] devices.

==Reaction==
===Critical reception===
Reviews of the film are generally positive. The film currently holds a 77% "certified fresh" rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]]. While this is indeed a positive score, it is the least favourably reviewed of the five Harry Potter films on the site.<ref name="rt">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_order_of_the_phoenix/|title=Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (2007)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=2007-07-25}}.</ref> ''[[The Telegraph]]'' headlined their review "Potter film is the best and darkest yet".<ref name=the-telegraph-review>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/06/29/wpotter129.xml|title=Potter film is the best and darkest yet|last=Frederick|first=Charles|date=[[2007-06-27]]|accessdate=2007-07-01|publisher=[[The Telegraph]]}}</ref> The ''[[New York Daily News]]'' gave the film four out of four stars, calling it the best ''Potter'' film yet and wrote that "die-hard Potter addicts will rejoice that Yates has distilled J. K. Rowling's broad universe with care and reverence."<ref name=ny-daily-news-review>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2007/07/08/2007-07-08_phoenix_hot_for_harry.html|title='Phoenix' hot for Harry|date=[[2007-07-08]]|accessdate=2007-07-08|last=Bertram|first=Colin|publisher=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Mirror|The Sunday Mirror]]'', giving the film four out of five stars, called it "a dark and delicious delight [and] a must-see movie".<ref name=sunday-mirror-review>{{cite news|url=http://www.sundaymirror.co.uk/showbiz/movies/tm_method=full%26objectid=19386975%26siteid=98487-name_page.html|title=Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix|date=[[2007-07-01]]|accessdate=2007-07-01|last=Adams|first=Mark|publisher=[[The Daily Mirror|The Sunday Mirror]]}}</ref> ''[[The Miami Herald]]'' gave the film three stars out of four and wrote that the film "is the first installment in the soon-to-be series-of-seven that doesn't seem like just another spinoff capitalising on the money-minting Harry Potter brand name. Instead, Phoenix feels like a real 'movie'."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/213/story/165548.html|title=Like Harry, movie has matured|last=Rodriguez|first=Rene|publisher=[[The Miami Herald]]|date=[[2007-07-10]]|accessdate=2007-07-10}}</ref> 

[[Imelda Staunton]]'s performance as [[Dolores Umbridge]] and [[Helena Bonham Carter]]'s as [[Bellatrix Lestrange]] were widely acclaimed; Staunton was described as the "perfect choice for the part" and "one of the film's greatest pleasures", "com[ing] close to stealing the show".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/news/articles/0,,2114641,00.html|title=Japan goes wild about Harry|date=[[2007-06-29]]|accessdate=2007-07-01|last=McCurry|first=Justin|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> Bonham Carter was said to be a "shining but underused talent".<ref name=the-times-london-review>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/film_reviews/article2000948.ece|title=Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix: the first review|date=[[2007-06-28]]|accessdate=2007-06-30|last=Lewis|first=Leo|publisher=[[The Times]]}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised [[Alan Rickman]]'s portrayal of [[Severus Snape]], writing that he "may have outdone himself; seldom has an actor done more with less than he does here".<ref name=variety-review>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117934037.html?categoryid=31&cs=1|title=Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=[[2007-06-29]]|accessdate=2007-07-01}}</ref> Newcomer [[Evanna Lynch]], playing [[Luna Lovegood]], also received good word from a number of reviewers including the ''[[New York Times]]'' who declared her "spellbinding".<ref name=nytimes-review>{{cite news|url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/2007/07/10/movies/10harr.html|last=Scott|first=A. O.|title=Hogwarts Under Siege|date=[[2007-07-10]]|accessdate=2007-07-29|publisher=[[New York Times]]}}</ref>

''[[Rolling Stone]]'' also lauded the three principal actors' achievements, especially Radcliffe: "One of the joys of this film is watching Daniel Radcliffe grow so impressively into the role of Harry. He digs deep into the character and into Harry's nightmares. It's a sensational performance, touching all the bases from tender to fearful." ''Rolling Stone'''s review also classified the film as better than the previous four installments in the series, by losing the "candy-ass aspect" of the first two and "raising the bar" from the "heat and resonance" of the third and fourth.<ref name=rolling-stone-review>{{cite news|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/movie/15087359/review/15289225/harry_potter_and_the_order_of_the_phoenix|title=Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix|date=[[2007-06-29]]|accessdate=2007-07-08|last=Travers|first=Peter|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>

''[[The Times]]'' (London) expressed disappointment that the three main actors were not able to fully advance the emotional sides of their respective characters, weakening the film.<ref name=the-times-london-review/> The ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' complained about a "lousy" storyline, alleging that the first twenty minutes of the film, when Harry is put on trial for performing magic outside of school and threatened with expulsion, but is cleared of all charges, did not advance the plot.<ref name=sf-chronicle-review>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/07/10/DDG3IQSIV91.DTL|title=Harried Harry: In his fifth outing, the wizard matures -- and faces plenty of grown-up problems|date=[[2007-07-10]]|accessdate=2007-07-10|last=LaSalle|first=Mick|publisher=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|page=B1}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote that ''Phoenix'' is "quite possibly the least enjoyable of the [series] so far," and that despite "several eye-catching moments", "the magic <U+2013> movie magic, that is <U+2013> is mostly missing." The review also criticised the underuse of the "cream of British acting", noting the brief appearances of [[Maggie Smith]], [[Helena Bonham Carter]], [[Emma Thompson]], [[David Thewlis]], [[Richard Griffiths]], and [[Julie Walters]].<ref name=hollywood-reporter-review>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/film/reviews/article_display.jsp?&rid=9447|title=Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix|last=McCarthy|first=Kirk|last=Honeycutt|date=[[2007-06-30]]|accessdate=2007-07-01|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>

===Box office performance===
The film opened to a [[List of biggest opening weekends|worldwide 5-day opening]] of $333 million, the third-biggest opening of all time, behind only ''[[Spider-Man 3]]'' ([[2007 in film|2007]]) and ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End]]'' ([[2007 in film|2007]]). Both of those films opened in many more markets <U+2014> ''Spider-Man 3'' in 108 and ''At World's End'' in 103, respectively, compared to ''Potter's'' 45. In the United States, tickets for hundreds of midnight showings of the film, bought from online ticket-seller [[Fandango (ticket service)|Fandango]], were sold out, making up approximately 90% of the site's weekly ticket sales.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=109&STORY=/www/story/07-10-2007/0004623179&EDATE=|title=SOLD OUT! Harry Potter Tickets are Flying Away on Fandango|date=[[2007-07-10]]|accessdate=2007-07-12|publisher=[[Fandango (ticket service)|Fandango]]}}</ref> In the U.S. and Canada, midnight screenings (very early morning on [[11 July]]) brought in $12 million<ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.yahoo.com/mv/news/va/20070712/118428478700.html|title="Harry Potter" works box office magic in debut|accessdate=2007-07-13|publisher=Yahoo!}}</ref> from 2,311 midnight exhibitions making the showings "the most successful batch of midnight exhibitions ever."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boxofficeprophets.com/column/index.cfm?columnID=10134|title=Daily Box Office Analysis for July 11, 2007|first=David|last=Mumpower|accessdate=2007-07-13|publisher=Box Office Prophets}}</ref> In one-night earnings, ''Phoenix'' is behind only ''At World's End'', which had debuted four hours earlier on its date.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=21911|title=Harry Potter 5 Opens to $12 Million|date=[[2007-07-11]]|accessdate=2007-07-12|publisher=ComingSoon.net}}</ref> 

In the U.S. and Canada, ''Phoenix'' earned an additional $32.2 million on Wednesday, post-midnight showings, making it the biggest Wednesday single-day gross in box office history, with a total of $44.2 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=60460|title=Harry Potter works magic at box office|date=[[2007-07-13]]|accessdate=2007-07-13|publisher=Ninemsn.net}}</ref> That amount tops Sony Pictures' ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'', which had held the record since 2004 with its $40.4 million take on a Wednesday. It is also the fifth-biggest opening day for a movie in history, surpassing ''At World's End's'' $42.9 million. It earned $1.9 million from a record-breaking 91 IMAX screens, the highest opening day ever for any IMAX day of the week, beating ''Spider-Man 3's'' $1.8 million. In the U.K. the result was similar. The film made <U+00A3>16.5 million during its opening 4-day run, breaking the U.K. box office record for the biggest 4-day opening weekend ever.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://film.guardian.co.uk/news/story/0,,2129017,00.html|title=Potter casts spell over UK box office|date=[[2007-07-18]]|accessdate=2007-10-24|publisher=Guardian Unlimited}}</ref>

''Phoenix'''s domestic gross is at $292.0 million in the U.S. and Canada, and at <U+00A3>49.2 million,<ref name=ukfilmcouncil-hp5uk>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukfilmcouncil.org.uk/information news/?p=D4A157781b2cb1C3C4XXTuF1E11A|title=Hot Fuzz, Harry and Bean boost the British film industry|accessdate=2007-11-14|publisher=[[UK FILM COUNCIL]]}}</ref> or $101.4 million in the U.K.<ref name=bom-hp5intl>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=harrypotter5.htm|title=HARRY POTTER AND THE ORDER OF THE PHOENIX - Foreign Total as of Dec. 9, 2007:$646,460,223|accessdate=2007-11-24|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> Overseas, it has grossed $646.5 million, the fifth highest-grosser ever overseas,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=2864|date=[[2007-09-23]]|accessdate=2007-10-04|publisher=The Numbers|title=The Numbers News}}</ref> for a worldwide total of $938.5 million<ref name=bom-hp5>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=harrypotter5.htm|title=HARRY POTTER AND THE ORDER OF THE PHOENIX|accessdate=2007-10-20|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> making it the second highest-grossing film of the year closely behind ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End|Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End's]]'' $961 million gross.<ref name=bom-2007wwgrosses>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2007&p=.htm|title=2007 WORLDWIDE GROSSES|accessdate=2007-12-27|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> It became the second-highest grossing ''Potter'' film worldwide,<ref>{{cite news|Url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117971702.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title='Bourne' supreme overseas|date=[[2007-09-10]]|accessdate=2007-09-10|publisher=Variety|last=McNary|first=Dave}}</ref> and the second ''Potter'' film to break the $900 million mark.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hpana.com/news.20169.html|title='Order of the Phoenix' second most successful film in franchise|date=[[2007-08-30]]|accessdate=2007-09-04|publisher=HPANA}}</ref> It is the [[List of highest-grossing films|sixth-highest grossing film of all time]]<ref name=bom-worldwide>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|title=All Time Box Office: Worldwide Grosses|accessdate=2007-09-25|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> and currently, the highest grossing 2007 film of Australia and the UK.{{Fact|date=November 2007}}IMAX Corporation and Warner Bros. Pictures announced that the film has made over $35 million on IMAX screens, worldwide, with an impressive per-screen average of $243,000 making it the highest grossing live-action IMAX release in history.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://biz.yahoo.com/prnews/070906/to484.html?.v=24|title=Harry Potter And The Order Of The Phoenix: An IMAX 3D Experience Sets New Record|date=[[2007-09-06]]|accessdate=2007-09-13|publisher=IMAX Corporation}}</ref>

===Awards===
Before it was released, ''Order of the Phoenix'' was nominated in a new category at the [[2007 MTV Movie Awards]], "Best Summer Movie You Haven't Seen Yet". However, that award was won by ''[[Transformers (film)|Transformers]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://mugglenet.com/app/news/full_story/942|title=Transformers beats Harry Potter at MTV Awards|date=[[2007-06-03]]|accessdate=2007-06-06|publisher=MuggleNet}}</ref> On [[August 26]] [[2007]], the film won the award for "Choice Summer Movie <U+2013> Drama/Action Adventure" at the [[Teen Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|title='Order of the Phoenix' wins 'Teen Choice' award|url=http://www.hpana.com/news.20165.html|date=2007-08-26|accessdate=2007-08-27|publisher=HPANA}}</ref>

The film was also nominated for several awards at the 2007 [[Scream Awards]] presented by [[Spike (TV channel)|Spike TV]], in the categories of "The Ultimate Scream", "Best Fantasy Movie", and "Best Sequel". Daniel Radcliffe was nominated in the "Fantasy Hero" categories, respectively.<ref>{{cite press release|url= http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/prnewswire/NYW14905092007-1.htm|title=Spike TV Goes Into the Woods for SCREAM 2007 at the Greek Theater in Los Angeles|date=[[2007-09-05]]|accessdate=2007-09-06|publisher=[[Spike (TV channel)|Spike TV]]}}</ref> The film won for Best Sequel and Ralph Fiennes won for "Most Vile Villain".<ref>{{cite press release|url= http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/prnewswire/NYSA00220102007-1.htm|title=Spike TV Announces Scream 2007 Winners!!!|date=2007-10-20|accessdate=2007-10-24|publisher=Spike TV}}</ref> The film picked up three awards at the inaugural [[ITV]] [[National Movie Awards]], taking "Best Family Film", "Best Actor" for Radcliffe and "Best Actress" for Emma Watson.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7019374.stm|title=Potter wins film awards hat-trick|accessdate=2007-09-29|date=[[2007-09-28]]|last=Pryor|first=Fiona|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> The film was one of ten nominees for a 2007 Hollywood Movie of the Year.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.filmthreat.com/index.php?section=festivals&Id=2134|title=2007 HOLLYWOOD FILM FESTIVAL ANNOUNCES LINE-UP|date=2007-10-10|accessdate=2007-10-10| publisher=Hollywood Film Festival}}</ref> It was also nominated for "Best Live Action Family Film" at the [[Broadcast Film Critics Association]] Awards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pressmediawire.com/article.cfm?articleID=4193|title='Into The Wild' Leads With Seven Nominations for the 13th Annual Critics' Choice Awards|date=2007-12-11|accessdate=2007-12-15|publisher=Associated Press}}</ref> It won the 2007 [[People's Choice Award]] for "Favorite Movie Drama".<ref name=pcawinners>{{cite web|url= http://www.pcavote.com/pca/history.jsp|title=People's Choice Awards Past Winners: 2008|accessdate=2008-01-10|work=PCAvote.com|publisher=Sycamore Productions}}</ref>

[[Nicholas Hooper]] received a nomination for a World Soundtrack Discovery Award for his score to the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hpana.com/news.20184.html|title=Nicholas Hooper nominated for 'World Soundtrack Discovery Award'|date=2007-09-07|accessdate=2007-09-08|publisher=HPANA}}</ref> [[Imelda Staunton]] was nominated in the "British Actress in a Supporting Role" category at the [[London Film Critics Circle]] Awards.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.variety.com/awardcentral_article/VR1117977651.html?nav=news&categoryid=1983&cs=1|title=London critics love 'Control,' 'Atonement'|date=2007-12-13|accessdate=2007-12-15|publisher=Variety}}</ref>

Currently, the movie is up for two nominations at the 2008 [[BAFTA Awards]], for "Best Production Design" and "Best Special Visual Effects".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/film-awards-nominees-in-2008,224,BA.html|title=FILM AWARDS NOMINEES IN 2008|date=[[2008-01-16]]|accessdate=2008-02-04|publisher=BAFTA}}</ref> It also is nominated for six awards at the 2008 [[Sony Ericsson Empire Awards]], organised by ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'', for Best Film, Actor (Radcliffe), Actress (Watson), Director, Best Sci-Fi/Fantasy Film and Score.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7225355.stm|title=Atonement leads Empire shortlist|date=[[2008-02-04]]|accessdate=2008-02-04|publisher=BBC}}</ref>

